snippet.textDisplay:
Colds, flu and allergies are still high and you dont want to convince yourself that you are infected with coronavirus. Bottom line, stay home, protect yourself if you have to work, and DONT PANIC. I am one of those people who panics everytime my heart skips a beat, I get dizzy, my hand goes cold, my stomach gurgles, or my blood pressure spikes. From my experience, the anxiety and the panic make things seem worse than they really are and I know this.

The fear drops when you understand that not everyone will get this, those that do may not have any symptoms at all, many who will get symptoms can manage at home, many of those who will need hospitalization will survive.

Yes, a lot of people are dying and more will die. We have 300 million people in the USA. Yes, it is terrible and you should care. Panicking or ignoring the steps to keep you and others safe is a bad thing. The odds of dying from this are extremely low, but out of 300 million people this equates to so many lost lives. The best you can do is not panic and do your best to lower the odds for yourself and others. That's the best you can do, and it is literally helping others and saving lives, and taking the burden off of the true heroes in the healthcare field.

snippet.textDisplay: Did he say he has had the flu half a dozen times? I at 45 have had the flu 1 time in my entire life. But I also get a flu vaccine each year. My coworkers son right after christmas 2019 was diagnosed with the flu type A, she does not make her son get a flu shot or shot of any kind. When he finally woke he had lost almost 30 pounds, before he got sick he was 5 foot 2 and weighed 157 pounds. He is 11 I might add. He also cannot walk, Talk,  or Feed himself. snippet.textDisplay:
A physiotherapist who deals with lung disorders and is a specialist in respiration passed some information on to me which is not yet in the public domain.

The virus is causing a build-up of phlegm on the lungs which is a lot thicker than usual. If you are infected and just laying in bed, the phlegm is solidifying, once that happens, it can't be removed.

1: If you are coughing up green or yellow phlegm, your body is fighting the infection.

2: If the phlegm is a dark grey colour, your body is losing the fight and you have pneumonia, call 999

3: If you are infected, huffing (the medical terminology) is effective at clearing your lungs. Take a deep breath and exhale as quick as you can, imagine a smudge on glass or a mirror and exhale as if you are trying to steam up a mirror, do it with as much power as you can muster. it helps with lifting the phlegm from your lungs. do this repeatedly all through the day, maybe 2 or 3 times an hour.

4: The old tried and tested method of a bowl of steaming hot water with some Vicks is effective too, put your head over the bowl, use a towel to cover your head, do this 5 times a day (or more if you feel it necessary).

5: DO NOT USE COUGH SYRUP, if you're coughing, you don't want to suppress the cough on this one as you need to be coughing phlegm up.

6: It may be difficult, but...it's important to not be laid in one position for too long, this is causing phlegm to pool in your lungs. If you are infected catnap throughout the day and night, don't seep all the way through. It's important to keep as mobile as you possibly can.

PLEASE PASS THIS INFORMATION ON TO AS MANY PEOPLE AS YOU CAN, IT MAY SAVE LIVES.
